<subSubSection id="C31C6500193FFFF86A8BA2427304FD05" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB9368B193FFFF86A8BA2427168FDAB" blockId="31.[189,324,549,575]" box="[189,324,549,575]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading id="D0F181E7193FFFF86A8BA2427168FDAB" bold="true" box="[189,324,549,575]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B972EA99193FFFF86A8BA2427168FDAB" bold="true" box="[189,324,549,575]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB9368B193FFFF86A8BA2337304FD05" blockId="31.[189,1398,596,657]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08193FFFF868B6A233732AFDFA" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[640,774,596,622]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplistylus">
<emphasis id="B972EA99193FFFF868B6A233732AFDFA" box="[640,774,596,622]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">amplistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘large stylus’ and referring to the enlarged left-side surstylus. The name is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
